            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Dmitri Solis-Garcia\u2019s name tells the story of his Bay Area upbringing. Born in the Philippines and adopted as an infant by a loving, unconventional family in Daly City, he was raised by his two mothers, Elena Garcia, a social worker of Mexican-American descent, and Anya Solis, a Russian-American literature professor. Growing up, his identity was a rich tapestry woven from the cultures he inherited and the one he actively explored, with weekends often spent alternating between family gatherings in the Mission District and exploring his Filipino heritage through community events.\n\nHis fascination with the intricate systems of life led him to UC Davis, where he pursued a degree in Molecular Biology. While he excelled in his studies, he discovered during lab internships that his true talent wasn't in wielding a pipette, but in orchestrating the complex dance of research and development. He found more satisfaction in streamlining workflows and motivating teams than in the solitary focus of benchwork. This realization was his pivotal career turning point.\n\nAfter graduating, Dmitri took an entry-level lab coordinator position at a biotech firm in Mission Bay. His innate organizational skills and understanding of the science propelled him upward. Now, at 37, he is a Senior Project Manager, guiding teams through the labyrinthine process of clinical trials.\n\nDmitri\u2019s life is rooted in the city\u2019s rhythm. He lives in a modest one-bedroom apartment in the Inner Sunset, cherishing his pre-dawn runs through the fog-laced trails of Golden Gate Park. His 8.5-mile commute is a daily ritual on the N-Judah light rail, a time for podcasts and observing the city wake up. Recently out of a long-term relationship, his social life revolves around a tight-knit circle of friends and weekly dinners with his mothers.\n\nHe finds deep satisfaction in shepherding potentially life-saving therapies toward approval. His future aspiration is to become a Director, but he also dreams of launching a mentorship program to guide underrepresented youth into STEM careers, a nod to the supportive, multicultural environment that shaped him. For Dmitri, San Francisco isn\u2019t just a place to work; it\u2019s a city whose mosaic of identities mirrors his own."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was ten, at a Filipino community picnic his mom Anya had brought him to. A woman offered him a piece of warm bibingka, the banana leaf steaming in his hands. He took a bite\u2014the sweet, sticky rice and salted egg was a flavor he\u2019d never had but somehow felt he knew. He saw Anya watching him, her smile not of a spectator but of someone witnessing a homecoming. In that moment, he wasn't just an adopted son; he was a bridge between worlds, and he felt a profound, quiet click of identity falling into place.\n\n2.\nAt thirteen, he stood awkwardly at his cousin\u2019s quincea\u00f1era in the Mission, feeling like an outsider amidst the swirl of Spanish and laughter. His mom Elena saw him. She pulled him onto the makeshift dance floor as a cumbia started. \"You feel the beat with your heart, not your feet, mijo,\" she whispered, guiding his clumsy steps. Laughter erupted as he stumbled, but it was warm and inclusive. He realized then that family wasn\u2019t about shared blood, but shared rhythm, and he belonged completely. This cemented his trust in love over lineage.\n\n3.\nIt was his junior year internship at UC Davis. A critical experiment was failing; samples were mixed up and a grad student was near tears. While others panicked, Dmitri felt a strange calm. He instinctively grabbed a marker, re-labeled the workflow on a whiteboard, and delegated tasks to untangle the mess. The lead researcher watched, stunned. The surge of satisfaction Dmitri felt orchestrating the solution was more potent than any successful result he\u2019d ever gotten from a pipette. He knew then his future wasn\u2019t at the bench, but guiding the people behind it.\n\n4.\nAfter a brutal week at work, he forced himself on a pre-dawn run in Golden Gate Park. He was 28. The fog was a thick, silent blanket, muffling the city. Cresting a hill near the de Young Museum, he stopped. Below, the ghostly tops of cypress trees poked through the shifting sea of grey. There was no one. It was just him, his breath, and the quiet heartbeat of the park. This wasn't just a city he lived in; it was a sanctuary that held him. That run became his ritual.\n\n5.\nThe final conversation with his ex was painfully quiet. They sat on opposite ends of the couch they\u2019d chosen together, the space between them feeling like a canyon. There was no shouting, just the devastatingly calm admission that their futures no longer aligned. He remembers tracing the seam on a cushion, focusing on the tiny, perfect stitches. The grief was immense, but beneath it was a bedrock of self-awareness. He was learning that some things, like clinical trials, can\u2019t be forced. Love, he realized, was one of them."
